<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Angel Dark, Demon Bright:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Andromeda, where’s Harper?” Beka asked. Andromeda’s hologram appeared in front of the First Officer. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Harper is in his quarters,” she said tersely.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Still mad at him?” Beka asked.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“A little,” Andromeda, replied, the edge in her voice somewhat softened. “I know why he did it. I just don’t like that he could.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“He won’t do it again,” Beka said, knowing Harper well enough to know that he wouldn’t. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Is that a promise?” Andromeda asked.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
Beka shrugged. “Let’s say it’s intuition.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I can live with that,” Andromeda said. Beka smiled.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Do you know what Harper’s doing?” Beka asked. She hadn’t seen the engineer since they’d returned from Witchhead Nebula, 300 years in the past.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
Andromeda shook her head. “He engaged privacy mode immediately.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I don’t like that,” Beka said, racing down the corridor past Andromeda. Her hologram flickered out of sight, though she couldn’t hide the worry from her face.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
Beka ran up to Harper’s door. She pressed the bell, but the door didn’t open. She knocked on the door several times, but still the door didn’t open.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Harper, it’s Beka! Let me in!”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I could help you, Beka,” Andromeda said, appearing next to the door.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Andromeda, door override; Alpha, six, niner.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
Andromeda nodded. “Authorization accepted. Acting First Officer, Beka Valentine.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
The door opened. Beka stepped inside. The room was dimly lit, but she could clearly see Harper sitting on his bed, leaning against the wall. He was staring ahead, looking at nothing. He didn’t acknowledge her presence when she entered. She sat on the bed, sliding closer to him.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I wanna leave, Beka,” he said, his eyes still staring ahead.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Why?” she asked.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Why?” he repeated in disgust, finally looking at her. “I’m a murderer!”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Harper—”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I killed thousands of people! I-I can’t stay here!” he shouted. He settled back down, taking deep breaths. “It wasn’t supposed to feel like this.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“What was it supposed to feel like?” she asked.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Like…we’d won. Like…I’d finally gotten back at all those Ubers for what they did,” he whispered. She put her arms around him. He put his hands on her arms, keeping hold of her, afraid to let go.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I’m sorry,” she said, leaning her head against his. “I wish I could take it all away.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I wouldn’t be me if I didn’t have it,” he said. She heard him sniffle.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“It’ll get better,” she said. “You just have to give it time.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Time on the Andromeda?” he said.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“If you really wanna go, then we’ll go,” she said. Harper let go of her arms. He twisted his body so he could look at her.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“No, I don’t wanna go,” he said.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
Beka smiled. “I didn’t think so.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
He stared at her, sadness still evident in his face. “Rommie hates me.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Oh, Harper,” she said, hugging him, “you lovesick little boy. Rommie doesn’t hate you.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Says you,” he said.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Like I said previously, just give it some time,” she said, making sure her arms were securely around him. Andromeda watched the two crew members hold each other. She could see the misery in Harper’s face and no longer had the heart to stay mad at him.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>The Ties That Blind:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
Harper entered the Maru, holding the golden trophy in his hand. He shined it with the sleeve of his shirt, smiling proudly when he saw his reflection. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Hey, Harper,” Beka said, meeting him at the bar. She gave him a pat on the back before pulling out a bottle of beer for him. He took it gratefully, snapping the cap off and taking a big swig. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Hey yourself,” he said. He placed the trophy on the bar, showing it off to Beka. She’d been the one to show him Infinity Atoll and got him into surfing when all he’d been interested in was fixing the Maru. She looked at the inscription on the bottom.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Seamus Harper. 20th Place, Pan Galactic Surfing Championship. Congratulations, Harper,” she said, getting some coffee for herself. His smile grew wider. “Last I’d seen, you were in 48th.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I got some really great waves,” he said. He looked down at the bar, tracing the edge with his finger. He was about to say something. “I hear Rafe stopped by.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
Beka sighed. “Bastard stole my disks. All of them!”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
Harper burst out laughing. Beka tried to keep a solemn face, but couldn’t help laughing along with her engineer. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Definitely sounds like Rafe,” Harper said. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I can’t believe how long it’s been since I’d last seen him, ya know?” she said, becoming reflective. It was a rare moment for Beka. Images of her childhood flashed before her eyes. “I didn’t realize how much I missed him.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Funny how that works,” Harper said. “People we love come and go. Some you expect to see again, others you don’t. Doesn’t make it any easier when they leave, but you feel a whole lot better when you see them again.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“You weren’t by chance hanging out with any of the Wayists on Infinity, were you?” Beka asked, chuckling at his insight.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Hey, I have my moments,” he said. “But I also know what it’s like to lose family. I had some cousins who’d get on my nerves. They were so annoying sometimes, but now…I’d give anything to see them again.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“That’ll never happen to us,” she said, placing her hand over his. He gave a feeble smile, but no one, not even Beka, could convince Harper that he was safe from the horrors he’d seen as a child. As much and as often as she told him they’d never be separated, there was always a saddened glint in his eyes that he knew nothing would ever last. It was a constant worry of Harper’s that one day she’d change her mind and leave him on a drift somewhere and never look back. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Yeah, I guess so,” he said, taking another swig of beer. Beka smiled contentedly. Life wasn’t so bad on the Andromeda. They were doing some good by restoring the Commonwealth and she had her friends with her. And with Harper, she had her family. She finally saw how much of a brother the little mudfoot from Earth had become. Even more so than Rafe.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“So, where ya gonna put the trophy?” she asked. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
Harper shrugged. “I don’t know. Maybe in the crew’s quarters next to my bunk,” he said. Beka fingered the trophy, smiling proudly at Harper again. His ego boosted even more, he showed all of his teeth when he returned the smile.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I know where we can put this,” she said. She picked up the trophy and headed to the cockpit. She placed the trophy under the many postcards she’d collected in the ten years she’d piloted the Maru. She stepped back, practically knocking Harper over. They steadied each other and gazed at the trophy’s new home on the Maru.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“It looks good there,” he said.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I couldn’t agree more.”<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Banks of the Lethe:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
She found him in the machine shop, frantically punching numbers into a console. On a plasma screen nearby, she saw several simulations being run. They were light years away from the black hole and he was still trying to figure out what went wrong. It was an inquiry that seemed to be turning into an obsession for the little engineer. He’d been losing sleep and was hardly seen anywhere else then in the shop. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Harper,” she said, cutting through the hum of the machines. He jumped. He normally never jumped when Beka called. She was careful to keep her voice low around him. It showed just how wrapped up in this he really was.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Hey, Boss,” he said, finishing the sequence of numbers. An angry alarm sounded. He hit the console in frustration. “Stupid piece of junk!”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Hey, save it for the gym, Rocky,” she said, using one of his own ancient Earth references. He smiled, but cradled his hand. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I don’t understand, Beka. It shoulda worked. Sarah shoulda been here,” he said. She noted the tinge of sadness in his voice. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Well, she’s not, Harper. So stop beating yourself up over it,” Beka said. “It was just meant to be that way.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Don’t tell me you’ve become a fatalist, Boss,” Harper said.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“No, I’m a realist. And I thought you were too,” she said. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I just know it shoulda worked,” Harper said. “Maybe…maybe if we go back to Sinti, then I could talk more with Hohne and…”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Harper, is all this about not making the machine work?” she asked. He stared at the plasma screen running his simulations. All of them failed. His gaze lowered, revealing his self anger.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“300 years, Beka. He was frozen for 300 years. And he had a chance to be happy and…” his voice trailed off from there. Nothing more had to be said for Beka to figure out what was really troubling the engineer. She put a hand on his shoulder.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“And you couldn’t make that happen,” she finished. Harper nodded. “Harper, Dylan doesn’t blame you for not being able to bring Sarah here. And he doesn’t think any less of you as an engineer. You are still a genius.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Yeah, well, a genius woulda found a way to make that thing work,” Harper seethed, pointing at the transporter. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“And one day you will,” she said. He looked at her, searching her face. For what, she wasn’t quite sure.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“How can you have so much faith in me?” he asked, genuinely curious. Beka chuckled.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Because you’re Seamus Zelazny Harper, super genius-ah!” she said, mimicking his own voice. Harper laughed. “Okay?”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Okay,” he said, sounding happier. He looked over at the transporter and sighed. “I’m not gonna be able to work with that thing staring back at me all the time. You wanna help me take this thing apart?”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Why?” she asked. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Spare parts. Some of the circuitry could go well with Rommie’s programming,” he said. “Besides, I’ve got the schematics down on a flexi already. I can rebuild at any time.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Then let’s get to work,” Beka said. <br>
<br>
TBC<br>
