<br>
Here ya go!<br>
<br>
<br>
____________________<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>All Great Neptune’s Ocean:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“So, no confessions today?” Beka laughed as she entered the Command Deck and found Harper repairing one of the officer’s stations. Trance was working at her post. She slightly smiled. Harper didn’t answer. He made no snide remark or even gave a reaction. He just continued working. Beka frowned. She walked over to Harper and leaned against the station he was working at.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Harper,” she said.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“What, Beka?” he asked, his voice quick to anger. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Sorry, am I bothering you or something?” she asked defensively. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Yeah, you are,” he answered, his tone short and snappish. He seemed surprised himself at how mean he sounded. He sighed, waving his hands in the air as he walked out of Command. Beka looked to Trance for an explanation. The purple girl shrugged in confusion. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“He was fine a few minutes ago. We were joking and laughing,” Trance said. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Until I came in,” Beka sighed. Trance looked confused again but Beka didn’t bother to explain. She ran out of Command. Harper was a ways down the corridor, but she caught up to him quickly.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Harper!” she called. He stopped and turned to face her.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I’m sorry, okay?” he said. He turned away to continue walking away, but she caught his arm, pulling him back. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Not so fast!” she said. He sighed in defeat and stopped again. “Now what was that all about? I was just teasing.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Well maybe I don’t think it was so funny,” he said. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Why? Because of Rommie?” she asked.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“It’s nothing I wouldn’t have done for you or Trance. I’d rather die than see one of you hurt,” he said, his voice solid and stern. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I know you would, Harper, and it’s one of the reasons I love you so much,” she said. He smiled. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“You’re not gonna get all mushy on me, are ya, Boss?” he asked. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Not my style,” she said. “But I understand why you did it, Harper. Your heart’s always in the right place, though I can’t say the same for your head.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Thanks, Boss,” he said.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“No problem,” she said. “So, what were you expecting Dylan to do after you confessed?”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Honestly? I hadn’t thought that far ahead,” he admitted. Beka shook her head, chuckling softly. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Typical.”<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>The Pearls That Were His Eyes:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
Harper walked into the Observation Deck. He saw Beka and Trance looking out at the stars, Trance’s tail draped over Beka’s shoulder. He thought it was a precious moment and didn’t want to disturb them. Unfortunately, he didn’t see the plant by the door. In his attempt to leave, he knocked into the plant. Dirt spilled on to the floor and the ceramic vase broke, making a loud crashing sound. Harper winced, his cheeks turning bright red when he saw Beka and Trance looking at him. Both were smiling.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Come on, Harper,” Beka said. Harper sulked, walking over to them with his head lowered in embarrassment. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Sorry, Trance,” he said, glancing at her. She smiled sweetly.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“It’s okay, Harper. I’ll go get a Maria bot to clean it up,” she said. She unwrapped her tail from Beka and skipped away.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“So, how was Uncle Skid?” Harper asked. He always managed to come up with weird nicknames for people. Even people he didn’t know.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“He was…fine. Just fine,” Beka said. She knew she’d made a mistake. Anyone could tell she was lying. In a way, she wanted Harper to know the truth.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Beka, could you be anymore obvious? Come on, what happened?” he asked. She could see the concern in his eyes. It was touching to know that he really cared about her. Something she couldn’t say for a lot of other people. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“He – um- he forced me to take flash,” she said. Harper’s eyes widened. She saw fire in his eyes. “He was after some data stored in the nanobots in my hair from my father. Then, he tried to kill me.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
Harper gritted his teeth. His fists clenched tightly. “I’ll kill him. Tell me where he is and I’ll shoot the bastard.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Harper, Harper, calm down! I’m fine, see? Everything’s good,” she said, grabbing him by the shoulders. There was such determination in his eyes, so much anger, that she almost felt like telling him where Sid was. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Flash? Beka, flash? I mean, come on, your dad was a flash addict! And he – he used it on you!” Harper said through his teeth.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I’m okay. No harm done,” she said.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“What?” he squeaked. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Okay, some harm done. But the point is, I’m home and I’m safe,” she said. Harper’s gaze softened. She waited until he nodded in agreement before letting go of his shoulders. She still wasn’t sure whether or not he’d go after Sid. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Do me a favor?” he said.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Sure.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Next time one of your relatives shows up or sends you a note, make sure I’m there,” he said.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
Beka smiled. “I think that’s doable.”<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Mathematics of Tears:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Why do people always wanna kill me?” Harper asked. He and Beka were walking to the Mess Hall after their escapade with the Pax Magellanic. For some reason, almost getting killed made them both hungry. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I don’t know, Harper. Maybe it’s your sparkling personality,” Beka joked.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I’m serous. I mean, it’s not like I go outta my way to offend people,” he said. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“They weren’t trying to kill us because of you,” Beka said. “They were just trying to kill us. You were a bonus.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Ha! Ha!” Harper said. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Well, it’s not all about you all the time,” she said, laughing.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Oh, and I thought the universe did revolve around me,” Harper laughed. Beka put her arm around his neck like an older sibling. She felt him slip his arm around her waist.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I will say one thing. You did a good job defending Dylan and Rommie,” she said. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Just doing my job,” he said.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Defending people you hardly know? That’s a new one for Seamus Harper,” she said. Harper grinned. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“It seems…different, ya know?” he said.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Like ‘higher purpose’ different?” Beka asked. Harper ran his free hand through his hair. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Man, I’ve been hanging around Rev too long,” he said.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I guess we’ll have to go outfit you in a red robe and medallion,” Beka said, hugging him as she laughed. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Hey, I happen to find red a very flattering color,” Harper said, grinning widely, showing his teeth. The playful sparkle in his eyes drew her in and she laughed from the gut. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
They reached the Mess Hall. Harper heard is stomach growl in anticipation of being fed. He pat his gut, telling it to shush and that it would be full soon.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“It’s got a mind of its own,” he said, proudly patting his stomach.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Come on, I’m in the mood for Italian,” Beka said, leading him inside.<br>
<br>
