<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Harper 2.0:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
Harper was staring at the holographic image of the X-1 on a tiny vid-screen next to the unfinished product. Beka watched his face contort from surprise to confusion in a matter of seconds. He picked up his nano welder and walked up to the giant hunk of metal. He stood there for a moment, contemplating his next move. He always liked to be five steps ahead of himself when working on a project. She saw him frown and shake his head. He put the nano welder down and stared at the vid-screen again. Beka saw it as her cue to step in.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“It’s not gonna put itself together,” she said, leaning against the wall.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I thought I’d try telekinesis. See if the pieces just fall into place,” he said, half smiling. Lines of frustration creased his forehead. “Maybe I’ll go talk to Trance and ask her if she knows anything about this thing.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Yeah, Trance would be the one to talk to about mysterious things,” Beka agreed.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Uh-huh. At least she might know something. Everybody knows something…except me,” Harper said quietly. It wasn’t quiet enough. Beka stared hard at her friend. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Now that’s not true,” she said. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Beka, for one very brief second…I knew everything. Everything in the whole universe!” he said, his voice elevated.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“And it almost killed you,” she added.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“A minor detail,” Harper said, shrugging.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“So, you want the ASU back in your head? You wanna have terrible nightmares that keep you from sleeping? You wanna kill Rev?” she asked, her tone intensifying with each question. Harper backed away. He lowered his eyes in shame. Beka almost regretted using a guilt trip on him, but sometimes it was her only option.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“No, I don’t want that,” he whispered. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Then what do you want, Seamus?”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I coulda fixed the entire ship! Rommie woulda been the baddest starship in the known galaxies!” he yelled. Beka sighed and stepped towards him. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Harper, for someone so smart, you sure can be dumb,” she said, rubbing the bridge of her nose.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“What?”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Do you think I know anything about rewiring computers? Do you think Dylan or Tyr could fix the slipstream drive as quickly as you can? Or build an android?” she asked. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
Harper shook his head. “No.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Then there’s your answer. You are still and always will be a valuable member of this crew,” she said. His lips curled into a slight smile. “And if Dylan doesn’t see that, then he’s blind. Besides, you’re valuable to me and that’s what’s important.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Thanks, Boss,” he said.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Hey, what’re bosses for? But there is one thing I need to talk to you about,” she said.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Yeah?”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“If you ever take my ship again, I’ll use your head as a basketball,” she threatened. Harper nodded quickly, knowing part of the threat was true. But he found it impossible to keep his face serious. He started giggling, which turned into a deep laugh. Beka feigned frustration, which only made him laugh harder. She finally joined him. When they stopped laughing and had calmed down, she noticed him staring at her intensely. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“What?” she asked.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
He smiled, his eyes glittering. “You really are beautiful.”<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Fear and Loathing in the Milky Way:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
Harper was still in the Maru after he and Trance had arrived back on the Andromeda. Trance was quick to go find Beka and show her the diary they’d found. With any luck, they’d be heading to Tarn Vedra within the next few days. He was sitting in the pilot’s chair, sipping another Sparky and staring out the window into the hanger. He heard Beka enter the tiny freighter, her footsteps treading lightly on the deck plating. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Quite an adventure you two had,” Beka said, showing Harper the diary. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Wasn’t exactly how I saw our good will mission going,” Harper said, taking another sip of the cola. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Well, Trance told me everything,” Beka said. Harper gulped.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“How much of everything?” he asked. Beka smiled wryly, raising an eyebrow.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Oh, everything, everything,” she said. “From the part where you protected her from Gerentex to the part where she threatened to kill you both.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
Harper smiled, remembering the whole adventure vividly. “Yeah, she stopped me from doing something crazy.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Define crazy. Because, according to Trance, you did some pretty crazy things,” she said. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“You know what I mean,” he said. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“She also told me she’d never seen you so ‘mean’ before,” Beka said. Harper fingered the control sticks. Beka waited. He usually answered when he felt ready. After hearing the things Trance told her he’d said, she was more than curious as to how the engineer was doing mentally. Out of all the members of the crew, he was the one most likely to revert back to his old ways of survival when things got tough. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I didn’t mean to act that way,” he said. “Gerentex, he…he made me so mad. He was hurting Trance!”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“She told me. She said you were very brave,” Beka said.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
Harper’s ears perked up. His smile grew. “She did?”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Uh-huh.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“She was pretty brave herself,” he said.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“You’re changing the subject,” she said.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“What was the subject?”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“You.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Ah, come on, Boss, we both know I’m not that interesting.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I know you’ve lived a hard life.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“No harder than anyone else’s,” he said, his eyes looking anywhere but at her. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“That’s bull and you know it,” she said. She took his chin between her thumb and index finger, gently forcing him to look her in the eyes. In a matter of seconds, she saw his eyes change from overly confident engineer to haunted mudfoot. Only Harper could pull off such a change. He managed to look older and younger at the same time. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I kept thinking of Earth and all the Ubers who thought they could push me around. Gerentex thought he could just use me and Trance to get what he wanted, and…” he cut himself off, searching for understanding.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Don’t worry, I woulda done the same thing in your shoes,” she said, smiling sympathetically. Harper returned the smile. He took another sip of his Sparky, but there was nothing left. He shook the can in disappointment.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“All out,” he said. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“We’ll have to restock. And try to pick up after yourself. Rommie’s tired of sweeping up Sparky cans in the machine shops,” Beka said. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Hey, the machine shops are my territory. I’ll clean it when I’m good and ready,” Harper said, following her out of the Maru. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“You tell that to Rommie.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I think I’d rather not.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“That’s what I thought,” she said. She noticed he was frowning. “What’s wrong?”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I still didn’t get my 84 grand!”<br>
<br>
Beka laughed, putting her arm around the engineer's shoulders. &quot;Harper, I think we're a bit beyond cash settlements at this point, don't ya think?&quot;<br>
<br>
Harper sighed defeatedly. &quot;Yeah, I guess you're right.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Besides, if this thing is real, we'll have more thrones spilling out of our pockets then we know what to do with,&quot; Beka said, thumbing the pages of the diary.<br>
<br>
&quot;You gonna tell Dylan about it?&quot; Harper asked. Beka thought for a moment, considering her options. Maybe showing Dylan wouldn't be so bad.<br>
<br>
&quot;I'll think about it.&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Star Crossed:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“He’s been idling in the machine shop for two days, Beka. He won’t speak to me or my avatar,” Andromeda said, trying to remain calm. Beka listened intently, arms crossed over her chest, though she felt like she was betraying Harper by even hearing the ship out.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Andromeda, Harper’s gonna do what Harper’s gonna do,” Beka said. Andromeda frowned, imitating Beka’s stance. The hologram wasn’t backing down. Beka sighed. “But I’ll talk to him.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Thank you,” Andromeda said, flickering out of sight.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
Beka stomped all the way to the machine shop Harper was occupying at the moment. He was fiddling around with several small parts. On the work bench were stacks of logic chips he’d scrounged a while back. He carefully took a logic chip and ran a laser scanner over it.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“How is it that one person can annoy an A.I. so easily and so often?” Beka asked. He glanced at her but didn’t give his usual bright smile. She sat down across from him, watching him work silently until he became uncomfortable. Harper didn’t like to be watched so intensely.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I haven’t done anything,” he said.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“That’s the problem. Andomeda asked me to talk to you since you aren’t talking to her or Rommie,” Beka said. Harper picked up another logic chip.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Why should she care if I talk to her or not?” Harper asked. Andromeda appeared next to Harper.  <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Because you’re my engineer and a member of my crew,” she said.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Privacy mode,” Harper said coldly. Andromeda frowned and blinked out. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Not exactly polite today, are we?” Beka asked. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Hey, I’m just showing her the same consideration she’s shown me since we met,” Harper said. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Aha!” Beka exclaimed. “So, that’s what this is all about.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I don’t know what you’re talking about,” he said, turning back to the logic chips. His eyes darted back to her. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Gabriel,” she said. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“What about the psycho?” Harper asked.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I know you were jealous.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“No, I wasn’t.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Liar.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Okay, so I was jealous. Sue me,” he said, his tone becoming angry. “Ya know, I work my ass off keeping her running at full capacity. I could cut a few corners and do a half way job, but I don’t. And do I get any thanks? Any appreciation? No! I get squat! And worst of all…!”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Yeah?” she said, egging him on so he could clear his chest. This had obviously been building since day one. Harper wasn’t one to speak out when people were mistreating him. It was a rare moment when he actually vented his anger and Beka wasn’t about to let him stop. But the anger seemed to leave him. His shoulders sagged. He put his elbows on the work bench, putting his head in his hands.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Worst of all…I was so easily dismissed,” he said, the sadness showing prominently in his voice and face. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“She was in love with him,” Beka said, trying to be partial. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Yeah, well love doesn’t mean ignoring everyone else. Especially people who try to help you,” he said. Beka watched him go back to work on the logic chips. She picked one up, examining it.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Whatcha doing?” she asked.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Eliminating glitches in the logic chips before I insert them into Andromeda’s program. I don’t want her pulling a Gabriel or a Pax on us,” he said, taking Beka’s chip. She leaned in closer, their noses practically touching. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“How much longer are you gonna be mad?” she asked. He paused in thought, thinking out the answer. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Gimme another day,” he said. Beka ruffled his hair affectionately. He finally smiled and went back to work.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
Beka walked a few feet down the corridor away from the machine shop before she stopped. Andromeda appeared, her face conveying her guilt. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I had no idea,” she said. Beka crossed her arms.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Harper’s sensitive, but he doesn’t let it show very often,” she said tersely. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I’m sorry,” Andromeda said. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Don’t apologize to me,” Beka said. Andromeda nodded and disappeared. Beka walked away, hoping not to talk to Andromeda for the rest of the day.<br>
<br>
