<br>
Hope you like it.<br>
<br>
_________________________<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>It Makes a Lovely Light:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
When Beka opened her eyes again, she wasn’t surprised to see Trance staring down at her, smiling. The first thing she felt was guilt over what she’d done to her crew. Trance saw the change in her face and smiled more sympathetically. She touched Beka’s arm.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“It’s okay. I forgave you already,” she said. Beka attempted a smile, though she didn’t feel any better. Trance wasn’t one to hold a grudge.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“You people are so forgiving,” Beka said. “How long have I been out?”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Two days. I gave you a sedative after your conversation with Dylan,” she said. &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Can’t imagine I’ve had any visitors since,” Beka said, trying to make a joke, though her voice fell flat. Trance smiled again.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I wouldn’t say that,” she said. Following Trance’s eyes, Beka looked to the other side of her bed. Harper was slumped in a chair, sleeping. On the floor were several discarded cans of Sparky cola and three flexis lay in his lap, ready to fall and join the cans on the floor. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“How long?” Beka asked.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“He hasn’t left since you’ve been asleep. He’s been directing all the repairs to the ship from that chair,” Trance explained. Beka smiled. It was the first smile that actually felt genuine. She wanted nothing more than to hug the sleeping engineer. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
He stirred, letting out a tired groan. Beka felt the sudden urge to close her eyes and pretend she was asleep. Remembering what she’d said to him, she wasn’t sure what kind of reception she’d receive from her friend, if she could even call him that anymore. He opened his eyes. Blinking out the blurriness in his eyes, he looked right at her.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Hey, Boss,” he said. She couldn’t hear a trace of anger in his voice, just relief.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Hey. How’re you doing?” she asked.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
He snorted. “I thought I was supposed to ask that question,” he said.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Old habits die hard,” she said. Beka looked at Trance. “Trance, could you give us a few minutes alone, please?”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Take all the time you need,” she said, walking away from the bed, her smile still bright and cheery. There was a moment of uncomfortable silence between the captain and the engineer. Harper looked ready to run despite his initial happy demeanor when he’d woken up. Maybe she should have had Trance stay. He seemed more comfortable with her in the room. Beka pushed herself up in the bed. Harper watched her every move.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Harper, I…I want to apologize for what I said to you,” she said, though she stared at the sheets. She was afraid of what his reaction would be.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“It’s…okay. I’m not mad,” he said quietly. Beka listened closely. She heard his tone, and, as carefully disguised as it was, she heard the hurt and the anger. She’d betrayed him in the worst way possible.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“You’re lying,” she said, looking up from the sheets to gaze into his fiery blue eyes. There was a war of emotions fighting across his face. He was trying to hold back, for her sake, but she knew better than to let him suppress something that made him this angry. “Harper, let it out.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“How could you?” he snapped immediately after her sentence finished. She flinched at the vehemence she heard.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I…I wasn’t thinking,” she said.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Bull! I know you, Beka. I know you better than anyone on this ship. And I know you’re always thinking,” he yelled. Every word dripped with anger. “You took it willingly. You knew the consequences and you took it anyway. Why?”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Because—” she couldn’t finish. She searched her mind for the answer but kept coming up empty. Then, suddenly, she saw the answer. And it shamed her just as much as taking Flash had. “Because I wanted to prove myself.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“To who? Me? Tyr? Rommie?” He paused. “Dylan?”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Yes,” she whispered. “I wanted to show him I was good enough. I wanted to be the one to take him back to Tarn Vedra.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I see,” he said. “So, get Dylan home and the rest of your crew be damned! What were all those speeches you gave me about not having to prove myself, huh? Why does it matter if Dylan thinks you’re a great pilot? I think you are. And so do Trance and Rev. That wasn’t enough for you?”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“No, it is. You know I value all of you,” she said, trying, in vain, to defend herself, though she didn’t see much point in it. Harper was right.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“You do realize what you did, right? You shot Rev! You practically killed Trance! And…”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Say it, Harper.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“And you hurt me. You used one of my biggest fears against me to get me to shut up. And it worked,” he seethed through clenched teeth. “Which makes you no better than the Ubers I left behind on Earth.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Harper, no!” she shouted. He closed his eyes. He winced as if the very words he spoke hurt him just as badly.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I wanna hate you, Beka. I wish I could treat you like everyone else whoever hurt me and just hate you!” he yelled. His eyes softened, glimmering with unshed tears. She reached out and touched his arm. He took in a huge breath, but didn’t pull away from her. “But I can’t. I can’t hate you. I love you too much to hate you.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
Beka burst into tears after his confession. She’d caused him so much pain, so much torment and he still loved her. Despite everything, he still loved her. Harper moved from the chair to the bed. He squeezed in next to her, wrapping his arms around her shaking body.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I’m sorry. I’m so sorry, Harper,” she sobbed. Harper only held her closer.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“It’s okay, Beka. I forgive you,” he whispered into her ear. “And I’m gonna be with you every step of the way. I swear you won’t ever touch the stuff so long as I live.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
Beka nodded against his chest, knowing he meant every word. He didn’t let go of her. Not when she fell asleep in his arms when crying exhausted her; not when they both woke up the next morning and she fought him tooth and nail when a craving for Flash hit her; not when she cried herself to sleep in his arms again, apologizing like crazy; not ever did he let go. <br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Its Hour Come Round At Last &amp; The Widening Gyre:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
Beka slammed her fists against the door to Harper’s quarters. He’d run out of medical after learning about his stomach being infested with Magog eggs. Even after Rev and Trance telling him they’d search for a cure and Tyr trying to convince him that there was hope so long as he was alive, he still ran. There were so many conduits on the ship, it could take days to actually find the little engineer, but Beka had a feeling he was closer than they all thought. When the door to his quarters didn’t open upon her request, she knew he was inside.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Dammit, Harper, open up! It’s Beka!” she shouted. She looked up. “Andromeda!”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I can’t open the door, Beka. Harper’s used a maximum override. Not even Dylan could get in,” Andromeda said, her voice echoing throughout the corridor. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Thanks a lot,” Beka grumbled. She grabbed her force lance, aiming at the door. “Want something done right, you’ve got to do it yourself.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
She fired on the code pad. The tiny device blew out of the wall, wires and circuits springing from the wall, sparking. The door immediately opened. Light filled the room. Harper was never one to hang around in dark places, but Beka couldn’t even find his lava lamp. The room was completely black. She entered cautiously, afraid she’d scare her friend. He was probably panicked, which meant he wouldn’t be in a right state of mind. She found the bed empty; the sheets weren’t even disturbed. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Harper, I know you’re in here. Come on, it’s me. It’s Beka. I’m not gonna hurt you,” she said, keeping her voice low. She listened to the room, waiting patiently for him to make a move or say something. She heard him. It was the tiniest of sobs, but she heard him. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
He was curled up in a ball in the far corner of his room. He was still wearing the medical gown; I.V packs attached to his neck and chest. Tears rolled down his cheeks from bloodshot eyes. His body shook. His arms were wrapped around his stomach. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
Beka wanted to cry. She’d never seen him so devastated. His worst nightmare had come true. She got down on her knees and crawled over to him. Cautiously, she touched his knee. He didn’t move, didn’t blink. He hardly seemed to know she was there. She moved closer, sitting next to him, waiting for his reaction. There was no reaction. Taking it one step further, she put her arms around him, wrapping him in her warmth and strength. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“It’s okay, Harper. I’m here. I’m here,” she soothed, whispering into his ear. More tears fell down his cheeks. His sobs turned into flat out crying. He leaned into her, taking his arms away from his stomach and hugging her waist. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I don’t wanna die, Beka,” he mumbled into her shirt. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I don’t want you to either,” she said, rubbing his back as more sobs wracked his damaged body. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I can feel them. They’re moving, eating me. They’re gonna kill me,” he said.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“You’re not gonna die, Harper. I swear it. We’ll find some way,” she said, squeezing his arm. “If I have to go to the ends of the universe to get those things out, I’ll do it!”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Don’t make me any promises,” he said. She lifted his head. They looked into each others eyes. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I don’t make promises lightly, Harper. You know that,” she said. “And if I say we’ll get them out, then we’ll get them out.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
He stared at her blankly. “I wanna believe you.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Then do it,” she said. He gave her his askew grin through the extra tears that fell down his cheeks. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Okay,” he whispered. She continued to rub his back in slow, circular motions. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Feel like going back to med-deck? Trance is a little worried,” Beka said. His smile faded.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“No,” he said, shaking his head violently. “I just wanna stay here.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Okay. How about getting into bed, then? You need to rest.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Yeah, sure,” he said. She helped him to his feet. He hunched over, grabbing his stomach. She helped him walk over to his bed, pulling out the blanket and sheets. He slipped under the covers easily, gripping his pillow, keeping his back to her. Instead of leaving to go tell the others, Beka scooted into the bed. Harper was lying with his back against her chest. She reached over and took his hand, keeping a protective arm over him. She listened to him breathe. At first, it was short gasps of air as his body tried to calm itself down. Then, his breaths became deep and calm. He kept hold of her hand like a lifeline. When he was finally asleep, she didn’t dare leave him. She didn’t want him to wake up alone, knowing what was in his body. She swore she’d keep him alive or she would die trying.<br>
<br>
