 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#001B55><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bslipstreambbs12353.showUserPublicProfile?gid=sambalam>Sambalam</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><table style='Filter: Glow(Color=#a42e2e, Strength=2)'><tr><td><span class='usertitle'>'The Parallaxis'</span></td></tr></table></span><br>  Posts: 36<br> <font color=#EFD68C>(2/20/03 4:50 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fslipstreambbs12353frm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=40.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Updates! :D</span><hr size=1> Guys! Where's the feedback? Come on, show me that you care! Please! Okay, I promsed myself I wouldn't beg. I'm not gonna beg.<br>
<br>
Instead, I'll give you another set to entice you.<br>
<br>
_______________________<br>
<br>
<br>
Exit Strategies:<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp  <br>
Harper sat amongst his projects in machine shop 6. He’d been hiding in conduits and basically avoiding everyone for the past three weeks, leaving many of his favorite gizmos and projects unattended. After his talks with Rommie and Rev, he decided to finally return to his old routine. But he could never really return to the old routine; not with thirteen little Magog swimming around inside his body. Just thinking about them made his stomach hurt. He grabbed his stomach, flinching from the sudden pain. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
Rev and Trance were working on making his medication into an inhaler, but for the moment, he was stuck having to get injections on a regular basis in medical so that the eggs stayed dormant.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
He heard the door open. Looking over his shoulder, he saw Beka storming in. His initial reaction was to smile and ask her what was up, but the murderous look in her eyes made him scramble to his feet.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Boss, what’s—” Beka pushed him before he could finish. He fell to the ground, narrowly missing one of his sharply pointed projects. Beka stood over him. He’d never seen her so angry, almost to the point of tears.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“What the hell were you thinking?” she shouted. She grabbed his shirt, pulling him up a few inches off the floor. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Beka, you’re gonna have to be a little less vague,” he said, trying to keep his voice calm. His rapid breathing, however, was proving to be harder to control. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
Beka glared at him. “Rommie told me.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
Harper’s face fell, the color draining away, leaving him a disgusting shade of pale. Beka let go of his shirt. He didn’t try to cushion his fall, his head hitting the floor hard. He felt one of the eggs move, but chose to ignore the pain. He watched Beka pace in front of him. Her hands swung back and forth in angry, clenched fists.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I can’t believe you! Killing yourself! Suicide!” she shouted.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“It’s my decision, Beka. Last I checked, my body wasn’t your property,” he argued.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Don’t get smart with me, Seamus!”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Don’t tell me how to run my life, Beka!”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“What life? You obviously seem eager to end it!”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I’ve got thirteen Magog eggs in my stomach! Excuse me if I think death is a better alternative to suffering!”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
They were both breathing heavily from the shouting. They hadn’t fought this badly since Harper’s first few months on the Maru.&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Fine! Just end it all! Never mind the people who’re trying to save your life!”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Oh, no! Don’t you turn this into a guilt trip, Beka! You don’t know anything about this! I’ve seen it. I’ve watched people I love – my cousins – suffer in horrible, agonizing pain with these little parasites inside them,” he said. He’d stopped shouting. His voice was low, revealing years of pain and loss. He was living his nightmare. “So don’t you dare try to make me feel bad because I want to die. Right now, death is my only foreseeable future.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
Beka resisted the urge to yell at him again. He gently rubbed his stomach, feeling another egg move. He wasn’t supposed to stress himself too much, but stress seemed unavoidable at the moment. Beka approached him. His muscles tensed. He was ready to bolt if she tried to grab him again.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Get up,” she said calmly. Harper quickly got to his feet. Beka pulled out her gauss gun. “Do you really wanna die that badly, Seamus?”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Yes,” he said. She winced when she heard his answer. She pointed the gauss gun at him. His eyes widened, but he didn’t try to stop her. She turned it around, handing it to him. <br>
“Go on, take it,” she said. He took the gauss gun hesitantly, unsure of her intentions. “Do it.”<br>
<br>
“Pardon?”<br>
<br>
“Kill yourself. End it now. Right here, in front of me,” she said. His eyes darted from the gun to her. He said nothing, but gripped the handle of the gun tighter. Slowly, he pushed the barrel against his stomach, both hands ready to pull the trigger. Beka had to fight her gut reaction to grab the gun from him. She just hoped her plan worked. Harper swallowed hard, his eyes beginning to sparkle with tears. He looked up at the ceiling, calling on some inner strength. Suddenly, he dropped the gun, a huge sob escaping. His arms hugged his stomach. Beka rushed to his side, wrapping her arms around him. They were both crying. <br>
<br>
“It’s okay, Harper. It’s okay. I’m here,” she whispered. <br>
<br>
“I can’t, Beka. I … can’t,” he cried. A question tugged at Beka’s heart. She knew she had to ask it.<br>
<br>
“You can’t kill yourself or you can’t kill yourself in front of me?” she asked. <br>
<br>
“Both,” he said, his sobs becoming quieter. She smiled, rubbing his back. She held him at arms length, wiping the tears away from his face with her thumbs. She cupped his face in her hands. <br>
<br>
“I know I’m asking a lot of you, Harper, but I need you to stick around. It’s selfish, I know, but I can’t lose you,” she confessed. He smiled, placing his hands over hers. <br>
<br>
“You won’t,” he whispered. <br>
<br>
She hugged him again. She felt him hug back, his arms tightly wrapped around her. Neither wanted to let go, but they found some way after a few minutes. It was a constant struggle from then on for the two friends to be far apart without wanting to run and find the other. In the middle of the night, when Harper succumbed to sleep and relived his nightmares over and over, all Beka had to do was touch his face and slip into bed with him and he’d feel the nightmares fade away. <br>
<br>
<br>
A Heart for Falsehood Framed:<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
They sat around the bar, drinking champagne and congratulating themselves on a mission well done, despite the few minor setbacks. Dylan had gone back to the Command Deck after a few drinks, leaving Beka, Harper, and Trance to celebrate. The celebration, however, felt oddly subdued compared to other post-theft parties they’d had in the past.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“You have to admit it was fun,” Beka said. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Yep! Nothing like theft to make you feel good about yourself,” Harper said.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Could we do it again?” Trance asked. Harper and Beka smiled.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“No, Trance, I don’t think we can do it again,” Beka said. “It wouldn’t look very good for the Commonwealth if the people trying to restore it were convicted felons.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Aren’t we already convicted felons?” Trance asked. Beka looked at Harper. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Maybe we should talk to Dylan about getting our records erased,” Harper said. Beka nodded in agreement. Trance took another sip of champagne. She offered some to Harper, but he declined. He had to limit his alcohol intake because of the ever present Magog eggs. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Do you guys ever wonder where we’d be if we hadn’t joined Dylan and Rommie?” Trance asked. The other two thought for a moment. In actuality, they’d never really wondered. Nor had they realized how much being on the Andromeda had changed their lives.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Probably still running salvage, or scams,” Beka said.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Jail, most likely,” Harper said. Beka saw his hand lightly rub his stomach. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“What about you, Trance?” Beka asked. Trance shrugged, her eyes darting around the room.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Oh, I’d still be with you, Beka,” Trance said, smiling. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I guess so,” Beka said with a smile. She couldn’t imagine her crew without Trance. Still, she gazed back at Harper. His saddened eyes stared off into space. She touched his arm. He jolted, looking at her in surprise. “Hey, what’s up?”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Oh, nothing,” he said. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Liar,” she said. She looked down at his stomach. “They bothering you?”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Huh? No, not much,” he said. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Why must you continue to lie?”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I was just thinking…” he trailed off. Beka and Trance exchanged concerned looks. Harper, while normally a very sarcastic and cynical person, was becoming increasingly melancholy. He didn’t joke as often as he used to and when he did there was always a little bit of bitterness edged in.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“About what?” Trance asked. He sighed, looking at them.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Would it have been so bad if we hadn’t joined up with Dylan? I mean, we had fun, right? Pirates in space? Maybe it would have been better,” he said.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Maybe you wouldn’t have these Magog in your stomach?” Beka said. Harper nodded ever so slightly. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Not that I’m complaining or anything. I know my purple princess is working on a cure,” Harper said, smiling at Trance. She returned the smile. “But, yeah, I wouldn’t have these things inside me and Rev wouldn’t have had to go through what he did. He didn’t deserve that.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“What’s the old saying? ‘That which does not kill us only makes us stronger,’” Beka said. Harper grinned. Rev had used the phrase many times in the past and present and probably still would in the future.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“We’ve certainly had our share of those situations,” he said. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Then maybe the best way to look at it is the positive side. You and Rev are still alive,” Trance said. Harper nodded. “And you’re both becoming stronger because of the World Ship. Rev is overcoming his inner demons just the same as you are. You’re just dealing with it in a more literal sense.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Assuming either of us win,” Harper said.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Harper!” Beka snapped. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I know, think positively,” he said. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“How about I think doubly positive? That way you don’t have to work as hard as it,” Trance suggested. Harper started laughing. Beka joined him. When the laughter stopped, Harper looked gratefully at Trance.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Thanks, Trance. That would mean a lot,” he said. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Don’t mention it,” she said. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“So are we done celebrating?” Beka asked. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I guess so. You can only dwell on this stuff for s long,” Harper said, smiling, really smiling at them.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
They left the Maru feeling better about the mission and a few other things.<br>
<br>
<br>
All Too Human:<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
Harper groaned as consciousness slowly came to him. His eyes remained closed but he was determined to open them. Lights made him squint but he kept them open. A blurry figure stood over him. Her golden hair was haloed by the lights, making her look like an angel. He already knew it was Beka. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Hey, Boss,” he said tiredly. She didn’t smile. He knew he was in trouble. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I swear, Seamus, you can be so stupid sometimes,” Beka breathed. As tired as he felt, Harper was fully awake. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“What’d I do?” he asked. Beka eyed him suspiciously.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“What’s the last thing you remember?” she asked. Harper closed his eyes, thinking about his last memories. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I was on the Maru. We were waiting for Rommie. Rev was telling me not to stress myself and…I’m kind of drawing a blank after that,” Harper said.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“You overdosed, Harper,” Beka said. Harper’s eyes bulged when he heard the information.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I what?” he exclaimed. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“When Rev and Tyr brought you in, Rev said you’d accidentally overdosed while repairing the Maru,” Beka informed him.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“There, see! It was an accident!” Harper said defensively. Beka crossed her arms over her chest.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“It shouldn’t have happened in the first place,” she said. “Harper, you know you have to be careful.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Hey, you weren’t there. I was under a lot of stress. It’s tough being the only guy who can fix everything plus having the added bonus of thirteen Magog in your gut. So, I’m sorry, okay?” he said angrily. Beka was staring down at the floor. They had been putting an awful lot of stress on him without considering what it would do to him with the Magog inside him. Considering everything that had happened since his infestation, she was surprised he hadn’t overdosed sooner. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“I – I’m sorry, Harper,” she said. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
Harper sighed, half smiling. “It’s okay. It’s not you fault.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“You could’ve died, Harper,” she said, her voice catching in her throat.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Well, I didn’t,” he said, some edge returning to his voice. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Not from the overdose. You could have died in the Maru,” she said. He stared at her in confusion. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“What?” he asked. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“The Maru. It was sinking. There was only one E.V.A. suit for the three of you,” Beka said. Harper still looked lost. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“There was? Then…how did I get here?” he asked. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Well, Rev was able to hold his breath and Tyr…” she trailed off. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Yeah? Tyr what?” Harper pressed. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Tyr…drowned himself so you could use the E.V.A. suit,” Beka said. She waited for the outburst exclamation she knew would come from the engineer. Surprisingly, it never came. Harper sat up in silent shock. His eyes glistened. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“He did? Why – why would he do that? He’s a Nietzschean! Drowning himself to save someone else doesn’t make sense!” he said. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Maybe Tyr was saving a friend,” Beka suggested. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“No. Nietzscheans and Kludges aren’t friends,” Harper said. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Harper, up here, you’re not a Kludge,” she scolded. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Yeah, I know,” he said. “But why?”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Maybe you should go ask him yourself,” Beka said. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Maybe,” he whispered. Beka wrapped her arms around him. Harper was startled at first, but eventually returned the hug. “What was that for?”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“For still being here so I can yell at you,” she said, ruffling his hair. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Well, if that’s the only reason you want me around,” Harper said, smiling. She smacked him in the back of the head.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Harper!”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Ha! Kidding,” he said. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Get out of here, psycho,” she said.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“With pleasure,” he said, bouncing off the bed. She heard him running down the corridor. Just barely she heard him call out, “Hey, Tyr, wait up!”<br>
<br>
